  "prompt": "What is the best Perl web app framework?",
  "response": "The \"best\" Perl web application framework depends on your specific needs, project requirements, and personal preferences. However, there are several popular and widely-used frameworks in the Perl ecosystem, each with its own strengths. Here are some of the top options:\n\n### 1. **Dancer2**\n   - **Description**: A lightweight, modern, and easy-to-use web framework inspired by Ruby's Sinatra.\n   - **Strengths**:\n     - Minimalistic and flexible.\n     - Easy to learn and quick to get started.\n     - Rich ecosystem of plugins.\n     - Ideal for small to medium-sized applications.\n   - **Website**: [https://perldancer.org/](https://perldancer.org/)\n\n### 2. **Mojolicious**\n   - **Description**: A full-featured, real-time web framework with high scalability and modern features.\n   - **Strengths**:\n     - Built-in support for WebSockets, non-blocking I/O, and real-time web applications.\n     - No dependencies outside the Perl core (self-contained).\n     - Great for both small and large applications.\n     - Comprehensive documentation and active community.\n   - **Website**: [https://mojolicious.org/](https://mojolicious.org/)\n\n### 3. **Catalyst**\n   - **Description**: A mature and feature-rich MVC (Model-View-Controller) framework.\n   - **Strengths**:\n     - Highly configurable and extensible.\n     - Suitable for complex, large-scale applications.\n     - Well-established and stable.\n     - Strong emphasis on best practices and design patterns.\n   - **Website**: [https://metacpan.org/pod/Catalyst](https://metacpan.org/pod/Catalyst)\n\n### 4. **Web::Simple**\n   - **Description**: A minimal, PSGI-based framework for building web applications.\n   - **Strengths**:\n     - Extremely lightweight.\n     - Ideal for small projects or microservices.\n     - Easy to understand and use.\n   - **Website**: [https://metacpan.org/pod/Web::Simple](https://metacpan.org/pod/Web::Simple)\n\n### 5. **Amon2**\n   - **Description**: A modern web framework based on Plack and PSGI.\n   - **Strengths**:\n     - Lightweight and fast.\n     - Good for building scalable applications.\n     - Inspired by Catalyst and Ruby's Sinatra.\n   - **Website**: [https://metacpan.org/pod/Amon2](https://metacpan.org/pod/Amon2)\n\n### Choosing the Right Framework\n- **For simplicity and quick development**: Dancer2 or Mojolicious.\n- **For real-time or modern web applications**: Mojolicious.\n- **For complex, large-scale applications**: Catalyst.\n- **For minimalism and lightweight projects**: Web::Simple or Amon2.\n\nUltimately, the best framework is the one that aligns with your project goals and your familiarity with Perl and web development concepts.",
